title: For Sale:  Custom Remington 700 7mm STW 26" Broughton 416R SS
postcontent:
Custom Remington 700 7mm STW 26" Broughton 416R SS , McMillan Hunter Stock - 2# Jewell Trigger - Trued .

freshly built custom Remington 700 chambered for 7mm STW. This rifle was built with an emphasis on accuracy by competitive benchrest shooter Pete Piper of Precision Barrel Work in Hempstead, Texas. The heart of this rifle is a 26" Broughton 5c 416R Stainless Steel Match barrel with a 1:9" twist rate. Broughton barrels are double stress relieved at the mill and triple stress relieved in the shop, pulled button-rifles, and hand lapped with a uniform land and groove diameter up to .0001" from breech to muzzle. The barrel is spiral fluted for decreased weight and increased heat dispersion, is threaded with a custom left hand helical muzzle brake fitted, and finally matte black cerakoted for a consistent appearance and durable longevity.

The receiver is completely trued, has a 1.070" thread tennon, and is pillar bedded in an epoxy gel to extract maximum accuracy. A Jewell trigger set to ~2 pounds further enhances potential precision. The bolt body is spiral fluted for decreased contact area, increasing the smoothness of cycling, and lending a high end custom look.

This rifle features a McMillan Hunter stock with grip and forend checkering and a Pachmayr Decelerator buttpad. It has an olive drab green, tan, and black marbled matte finish.

title: For Sale:  5.56mm AWC Suppressor / Silencer SPF
location: Grey Forest (NW of SA), San Antonio, Texas
postcontent:
SOLD PENDING FUNDS

Offered for sale is this heavy-duty suppressor for a 5.56mm / .223 Remington rifle. In fact as close as I can tell the bore of the suppressor is about 6.75mm or .266 caliber, so I would think it could be used on any of the 6.5mm weapons — or of course, anything smaller. It is threaded 1/2-28, which is the standard thread for 5.56mm AR-15's and other weapons chambered for that caliber. It also works quite well as a .22 suppressor.  It is a very strong unit, constructed of 100% stainless steel with each component solidly 360 degree welded, and is made to withstand both semi- and full-auto fire.

Dimensionally, it is 7.5" long, 1.45" in diameter, and weighs about 25 oz. It has a matte crinkle finish The markings on the suppressor are as follows:

[LOGO]  AWC SYSTEMS TECHNOLOGY
PHOENIX, AZ
[SERIAL NUMBER]
CQB  5.56mm

AWC no longer makes this specific model, but they verified that it is an earlier model of the Raider model they currently offer, described on this page: https://awcsilencers.com/shop/raider/ There are minor cosmetic differences from the images on that page (compare with the picture presented here), but the other characteristics listed fit with this suppressor.

I am not the original owner of this suppressor, but I have owned it for years, used it occasionally and kept it cleaned out. There is no thread, muzzle or baffle damage. It is every bit as functional as the day it was manufactured, and I can find only very minor marks in the finish. All in all, it is ready for duty.

If you've never owned or used a suppressor, let me tell you, it's easier and less expensive than you may think — and if you want to take the leap, gi'me a holler and I can talk you through it, even help you with the paperwork if you decide to move forward.

I'm not a dealer, just a private owner, but that works to your advantage since any dealer would charge you a transfer fee, which usually runs $75-100 for class 3 transfers. Sometimes they charge sales tax too. As long as you're a resident of Texas, there's no need for a dealer to be involved — you buy it straight from me, just like any other firearm, except that the BATFE has to bless the transfer first. No problem with the paperwork, I've done it a lot, even have some good templates to make it easier. Feel free to ask me any questions you have – I'll be happy to read you in on anything I know about, and I'll also tell you if I don't know.

All laws apply here. I will expect you to pay for the purchase up front, and you will have to complete and submit paperwork to the BATFE for their approval before I can hand you the suppressor, but if you can legally own a pistol, you can probably own this suppressor. There's a $200 tax that has to be paid to the BATFE one time, a little more paperwork than a firearm, and you'll have to wait a few months, but believe me, it'll be worth it!

SOLD PENDING FUNDS
